es, such as viewing her work through a lens of psychoanalysis, modernism, or Irish or British history and which emphasise Bowen’s innovation not as central to our understanding of the changes happening in twentieth-century literature and history, but as instead a point of ‘difficulty’Recognises Bowen’s innovation, experimentation and her impact on her contemporaries and literary descendants From experiments in language and identity to innovations in the novel, the short story and life narratives, the contributors discuss the way in which Bowen’s work straddles, informs and defies the existing definitions of modernist and postmodernist literature which dominate twentieth-century writing. The eleven chapters present new scholarship on Bowen’s inventiveness and unique writing style and attachment to objects, covering topics such as queer adolescents, housekeeping, female fetishism, habit and new technologies such as the telephone.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aCreation (Literary, artistic, etc.). 0aModernism (Literature). 0aPostmodernism (Literature). 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Feminist.2bisacsh1 aBennett, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGasston, Aimee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGildersleeve, Jessica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoogland, Renée C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, Laurie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKelaita, Jasmin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaude, Ulrika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShort, Emma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Patricia Juliana , e